South African Stocks Decline For Second Day, Led by BHP on Lower Dividend

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-02-16T08:52:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-16/south-african-stocks-decline-for-second-day-led-by-bhp-on-lower-dividend.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index declined for a second day, losing 39.73, or 0.1
percent, to 33,020.55 at 10:05 a.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, dropped for a second day, losing 3.38 rand, or 1.1
percent, to 291.97 rand. BHP reported first-half net income of
$10.5 billion. Analysts had forecast profit of $10.2 billion in
the period. Its first-half dividend of 46 cents, up from 42
cents a year earlier, missed a projected dividend of 48 cents,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.    Hyprop Investments Ltd . (HYP SJ), a real-estate investor,
rose for a second day in three, gaining as much as 95 cents, or
1.7 percent, and last trading up 15 cents, or 0.3 percent, at 55
rand. The company said because of differences of opinion with
the board on operational issues, Mike Rodel will step down from
his position as chief executive officer after the annual
earnings presentation in March.  WG Wearne Ltd. (WEA SJ), a South African concrete maker,
gained as much as 3 cents, or 17 percent, its biggest jump since
Jan. 27, and last traded 1 cent, or 5.6 percent, higher at 19
cents. The company said it is in unspecified talks, a day after
saying it applied to the High Court to seek a moratorium on debt
repayments.  To contact the reporter on this story:
